{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d4e8189-d0ad-41c9-bbae-ba9c25465d01","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK required. Inside the container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- For **arm64** containers, use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64`.\n- Use `docker cp` to copy the resulting `.nettrace` file out, then open it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n- If you'd rather bake it into your image, add the `curl` line to your `Dockerfile`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0145294e-1191-4999-8e9c-7098369b34c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK needed).\n2. For .NET 8 on Linux, you can download the single-file version from the dotnet diagnostics releases.\n\n\n3. I can use `curl` to download it directly into the container, which is the most straightforward approach.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"DA1E:23CF76:226B174:2600123:6A03D499"},"id":"ab18f239-f008-4947-bac1-3df7c08727b7","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:32:19.654Z","parentId":"2e7fa76c-f1db-4ad9-8f53-80bc101bdbb3"}
